family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aces for children who might obtain higher exam results thereby boosting a school’s performance.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 35.65pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ten years ago I was an Assistant Headteacher of a Secondary school and we excluded a child as an absolutely last resort. You might say that it is important to m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aintain high standards of behaviour and I would agree with this. However, the nature of the exclusions I have witnessed are unfair and unjust. This can only lead to resentment on the young people’s part. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 35.65pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Last week a Year 12 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Somali boy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">permanently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">excl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uded for hitting another child</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It was his first offence. There had been co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nsiderable provocation. The other child</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> only made a statement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of one sentence and a half. Of course the offence was wrong but there was no attempt from the school to help the childr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">en to learn from their mistakes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The boy had achieved reasonable grades at his secondary school and had had no real problems. Within half a term at a new Academy he has been excluded. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">That young person is now a NEET. At the Governor’s meeting the Chair of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the panel was clearly biased in favour of the Headteacher.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> I think it is highly dangerous to treat children in such a careless fashion.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 35.65pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Across London children are being informally excluded by being “persuaded” to leave and find other schools or are being p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ut into alternative provision. Where this provision is good and the young person is receiving a service that is more tailored to his needs this is good. However, I am concerned we are churning o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ut children that will become the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">future problems of society.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here is a lot of government money and energy going into helping NEETs into work but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">you seem to be making it easy for schools to churn out NEETs by the increasing ways they are excluding children.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 35.65pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is no independent accountability for these exclusions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Headteachers are taking advantage of it and children and parents are feeling increasingly powerless and alienated.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 35.65pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I think it would be useful to find out how many young people are leaving at Year 10-11 and where their destinations are. Although the freed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">om that headteachers have in Academies can be useful for curriculum it can be abused in order to drive up results. Exclusions should be judged completely independently and harsh sanctions applied if they have been applied unfairly or disproportionately.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>